00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And we our strategy that we use to basically accomplish this mission is twofold.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:17.000
First, we have created three very successful open source projects, Apache Spark, which is scalable in-memory data processing, Delta Lake, which is scalable data storage and management, and MLflow, which is used to manage the entire machine learning lifecycle.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:25.000
In addition to this commitment to open source, we also have developed a managed service that is beloved by many of our customers.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:32.000
We have over 6,000 employees across the world. We're very successful, thankfully, in terms of our revenue and investment from top firms around the world.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:38.000
And we're the inventor of the data lake house paradigm, as well as a pioneer in generative AI.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And we're very fortunate to have been recognized for these accomplishments.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Now, what I would like to begin to go into is sort of, you know, our view on data and AI is that it's universal.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And everyone already knows that this has impacted every single industry, every single sector of the economy.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And we believe that the companies that kind of win in their industry will become themselves data and AI companies.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.000
This is easier said than done, though.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And if you look at what data and AI means, it's actually a collection of very different but related technologies.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
So, for example, you have everything from data warehousing and AI to streaming, real-time analytics, data science, machine learning.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
And then you have to govern all these different sort of use cases and technologies.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Not to mention that you have the emergence of generative AI and the promise that it kind of brings to the table.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So it's very, very hard for organizations to kind of wrap their heads around all of this and make them, you know, successful with all of this.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Our effort has really been to simplify all of these things.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And we've done so with the data lake house.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
So if you're not so familiar with the lake house, let me just kind of walk you through it quickly.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
So the concept of a lake house is essentially it's a portmanteau of a data warehouse and data lake.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So you have the structured data and performance and consistency that you have with the data warehouse alongside the unstructured data and sort of the open nature of a data lake.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So our data lake house is built on an open data lake.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Basically, you use cloud object storage, S3, ADLS, GCS to store all of your data.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And then you can unify your data under one single storage and management system, which is Delta Lake is the underlying technology for that.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Once you have all of your data in storage and you're managing it with Delta Lake, then you can secure and govern it with Unity Catalog.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:45.000
And then once you've secured and governed your data, all of your data, one copy of the data, then you can kind of unlock these different pillars of data and AI and analytics.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:52.000
So we kind of pioneered this concept in 2020, and we're really, really excited and happy to announce that this has been pretty successful.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:57.000
We've had 74% of global enterprises have adopted the lake house architecture.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So this really speaks to kind of the power of it and sort of the simplicity and unification of it.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
