Okay, so Posit has its roots in open source software and primarily in the form of the RStudio IDE.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:25.000
So if you've ever used the R language, odds are at some point you've used the RStudio IDE, which is where Posit has come from, right?

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
Historically, we continue to be the maintainers of this open source IDE today.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And it is the preferred development environment for developers and data scientists that are working with the R language.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
We also contribute heavily to the open source community through a variety of open source packages.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:48.000
These include a number of popular R packages like the tidyverse and its collection of packages for data analysis and data science,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Shiny for interactive applications, Quarto for dashboarding and for reproducible reporting,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Reticulate allows R users to work with Python directly from the R language, and many, many more.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:10.000
One of the things that's exciting as we look at where Posit has been and where we're going is our renewed and continued investment into not only R but also Python,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:20.000
so that we focus not just exclusively on a single language, but instead we focus on promoting open source technology for data scientists,

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
regardless of whatever language that might be in.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Just a little bit of historical context, and this is not comprehensive at all, but just to give some context as to what Posit is as a company and who we are.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
In 2011 is when the RStudio IDE was first introduced, again, as an open source tool that's available to download,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:43.000
and it continues to exist today as an open source desktop installation that anybody can go and use.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:56.000
That's something that we firmly believe in is providing those open source tools to give anyone in the world access to the tools necessary to be data literate and to make informed decisions based on data they have access to.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
Shiny, the package for building interactive web applications in R was introduced in 2012.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:12.000
Our first enterprise software where we were charging customers to run software in an enterprise environment with additional features that were attractive to the enterprise were introduced in 2014.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And then in 2020, we announced that we were becoming a public benefit corporation, and included in that effort is some specific promises that we make to our community as part of our company mission.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:32.000
And then in 2022, the company rebranded from RStudio, which had been the name of the company up until that point, to Posit.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
So if you've ever worked with RStudio, the company, we are one in the same.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:45.000
We just now go by the name of Posit, which helps us, again, kind of push forward our mission of open source data science, regardless of the language of choice.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:55.000
One thing that's pretty unique about how Posit operates is that a lot of what we do today on the engineering side is focused on open source technology and open source packages.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Again, we continue to support the open source RStudio IDE that continues to be very, very popular amongst data scientists and users.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
But then we also have this growing collection of packages that we work to support as well.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:13.000
That we firmly believe that this open source commitment is beneficial across the board.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:21.000
It helps users get early access to tools and technology that enable them to be successful in working with data at no financial cost.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:33.000
And then it also enables them to take those tools into a professional context, into a commercial environment, where we can support those tools with our enterprise products that customers purchase.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And then that purchase, that income that we receive there, gets reinvested back into the open source side.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And this is something that we refer to often as the virtuous cycle.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:49.000
We give to the open source side, and that eventually promotes commercial adoption of the tools that we provide.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:57.000
When we talk about the commercial side or the enterprise side of Posit, there's really three main components that we'll talk about.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
Each of these will be highlighted to some extent in our conversation today as we talk about Databricks.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:16.000
But just to give those who may be unfamiliar an idea, we offer a tool called Posit Workbench, which enables users to access common data science development environments through a browser in a centrally managed type of way.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:23.000
So through Posit Workbench, you have access to the RStudio development environment, VS Code, Jupyter Notebook, JupyterLab.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:35.000
And there's a number of different ways that Posit Workbench can be configured to run within an organization and can be designed architecturally to fit within whatever type of environment an organization is running in.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:45.000
As a complement to Posit Workbench, we offer Posit Connect, which serves as a bridge between the developers and the data scientists and the end users.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:13:00.000
So Posit Connect allows developers to publish and share the work that they've done inside of a development environment, whether that work is something interactive, like a Shiny application that was built in R, or a Streamlit application that was built in Python, or even a web API that was built in R or Python.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Those can be published to Posit Connect.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.000
And then other users of the organization, whether they're business users, decision makers, they may be downstream processes that are consuming APIs.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:25.000
Those can then utilize the work that's been done by the data scientists and the developers, because it's hosted and shared in a central location that's secured and governed according to the rules of the business and the rules of the organization.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:41.000
As a kind of behind the scenes component to all this, we also offer Posit Package Manager, which enables organizations to provide a secure and essentially regulated way to have users access R and Python packages.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Organizations can define which packages are part of their ecosystem.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Posit Package Manager supports snapshotting by date.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:14:06.000
So if I had an analysis or a thing that I worked on two years ago, and I need to roll back to packages as they were at that point in time, Posit Package Manager makes all that very simple, very straightforward, and is a benefit to organizations where reproducibility and security are of most importance.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:16.000
So what we'll talk about now as we move forward today is how all of these different pieces, the open source side, the commercial side, how does all this work together with Databricks?

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:25.000
