00:39:54.000 --> 00:40:09.000
I need to define whether I'm using SSL. There's this thrift transport argument. I need to define what auth mechanism I'm using and provide a user ID and password, whether that's a username and password combination or a token and the personal access token that I'm supplying.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:15.000
But I have a lot of details that need to be provided in order to create a connection to Databricks.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:30.000
Well, because we've done a lot of work inside of Workbench to simplify things like credential management and other components necessary to access Databricks, we're introducing a new function to the ODBC package and upcoming release called Databricks.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And this function exists to help facilitate connections to Databricks through ODBC, whether that driver is the ODBC driver that you install from us, or it's the ODBC driver and connector that you install and download and install from Databricks themselves.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:58.000
With this new ODBC Databricks function, we can get rid of essentially everything that we saw in the previous connection string and instead just supply the HTTP path that we need. And that's it.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:07.000
And so to highlight this, if we run this chunk of code right here, we'll see that we have an ODBC connection into Databricks.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:21.000
And this ODBC connection will give me a similar view into Unity Catalog as what we saw with Sparklyr. So once again, I can expand out and I can look at, okay, here's this new fork schema, here's this table inside of there, here's the different values that are included in that table.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:36.000
And if we come back here, we can see that we now have two different connections. We have an ODBC connection into Databricks, and then we have a Sparklyr connection into Databricks that are both being supported from this local environment.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:45.000
Once we've created these connections into the Databricks environment, we can create local references to data tables that might exist in the Databricks environment.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:57.000
So for example, if I run this new fork command here, if I run this line of code here that uses the table function or the TBL function to reference the data inside of Databricks,

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:05.000
so notice that I'm referencing demos, new fork, and then the new fork reports, this will create a local reference that points to that data inside of Databricks.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:13.000
In fact, we can see this because if we run the head function, which would typically return the first six rows of a given dataset, and then we run show query,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:22.000
this will show me how this ends up being translated on the backend in the Spark SQL that gets executed on Databricks and the results come back into my environment.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:29.000
The key here and the benefit of this is that I can keep all of my data in Databricks as long as I need to and work with it there.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:37.000
And then when necessary, I can move whatever summarized version of the data I need back into my RStudio environment.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:42.000
So if we wanted to, like, for example, right, we had this UFO sightings data.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:53.000
If we wanted to explore this data and gain some insight from it, we could do something like take the new fork data and filter by date time and then calculate by month how many UFO sightings that were from the dataset,

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
and then we could explore what that might look like.

